1930 Wednesday 1, Jan.

Cook and I both worked practically all day today on Searl's collection of last summer. Would have finished it but ran out of tags. I worked on the clerical end until 10 P.M.

Page Edit History:
  • lwilliams 05/06/2011 06:16 PM
  • tburress 03/17/2011 04:05 PM

Jan. Thursday 2, 1930

Today received Woodbury's description of Crotalus concolor probably anticipating my Crotalus conflentus decolor. Serves me right for delaying so long to get connecting links in this species. Have known about this for 14 months.

1930 Sunday 5, Jan.

Today finished repeated rereadings of the confluentus paper.
Also did much miscellaneous record work.
Today Cook completed his work. For the past several days he has been packing rattlers for shipment.
All rattlers ready for shipment.
no 18664 of U.S.N.M. is lost.

1930 Saturday 11, Jan.

The new shelving on the east side of my stoneroom having
been finished, today completed the rearrangement of all specimens. For the first time had room for all rattlers.
Attended meetings of the Scripps institution of oceanography and annual meeting of the fellos of the Society of Natural HIstory of S.D.
Philys brought in a medium sized specimen of Gerrhunotus
sancicauda webbii. A cold rainy week.

Spent most of the day on statistical work-particularly the annual snake list. Took lots of time to check the 3 on al distribution.

Jan. Tuesday 14, 1930

Received the confluentus ??? back from Abbott today.

Received 3 specimens of oreganus from Washington State normal school, Cheney, Wash. indicating that oreganus goes
practically to the state line.

Went to Rotary meeting at El Cajon this noon. 31 miles nothing seen.

1930 Wednesday 15, Jan.

Today went out to snow at Pine Valley, about 1 foot deep.
First snow at terrinitos. Rained all the way back. 96 miles; nothing seen.

Confluentus paper to printer today.

Bogert calls to my attention a Trimorphodon in L.A. museum from dead man's point, near Lucerne Valley, San Bernardino Co.

1930 Saturday 25, Jan.

Today I completed the S.D. county lizard maps from all sources. All S.D. county maps are now up to date for the first time.

Began to tabulate the atrox group for the lower California paper.

Jan. Sunday 26, 1930

Continued to tabulate the atrox group. Made good headway but it is a tedious job.

Saw Abbott from 4:30 until 6. Discussed the proof of the confluentus paper.

30 miles in county.

1930 Thursday 6, Feb.

Went to Los Angeles today with Holloway. A clear warm day. Nothing seen. 61 miles in the county.

Stopped at Schubach's at 3 P.M. but he was not open.

Saw Weinbergs material. He had 6 atrox, 3 oreganus, 1 scute from northern Sonora and about 15 cerastes from southern Arizona. He gave me 3 atrox, 3 oreganus, 1 scute, 3 cerastes. The atrox are the same as any ariz. specimens.

The cerastes are from 5 mi. N.E. of sells or indian oasis. All S.W. of Tucson.

Black oreganus, atrox and scute are from 20 mi. S.E. of Sasabe about 10 mi. south of line. Under flat rocks. Very cold about Nov. 27th partly dormant. All together in radius of a few miles.

In the evening heard Roehing address keys society. Nothing new. No specimens on exhibit.

Feb. Friday 7, 1930

Worked a short time in the afternoon in L.A. museum. Returned after dark to S.D. arriving 10:30.

1930 Saturday 8, Feb.

This afternoon pickled the 10 Weinberg specimens and about 6 others. Made scale counts on 8 of the 10. Noted that 3 (at least) of the Weinberg rattlers were badly infested with worms.

1930 Sunday 16, Feb.

Spent most of the day fixing up the Bancroft expedition with material for collecting reptiles. Talked with Griff at considerable length.

Returned specimens to Brode, Leffingurell and Barlow.

Back still bothering me. Haven't enough pep to work in lower California.

Feb. Monday 17, 1930

Today furnished Bancroft with 4-5 gal milk cans 2/3 full of 1-10 formalin and 10-2 qt. jars in a special box. Also a .22 rifle. They promise to collect.

1930 Tuesday 18, Feb.

Cook mentioned Anmella from monument on mexican side of line - taken Feb 15th.
Went to LA in the afternoon. A clear warm day; 62 miles in county.

1 gopher small D.O.R. Torrey Pines Mesa
1 " " " Carlsbad
1 " " " Dana Point.
1 " " " Opp. Newport.

Saw Schulach collection nothing of interest.

Feb. Wednesday 19, 1930

Returned from Los Angles in the afternoon. 5:30-6:00 Nothing seen. 62 miles in county. Slightly cooler than yesterday.
Feb. 19 continued.
of cerastes. Around little lake stephensi is found (as proved by 3 skins) but is not common. He thought he had only seen 8 or 10 in as many years. oreganus occurs in the timbered regions of the sierras but does not come far down. He had found them at 9000 ft. Other snakes found at little lake are Boyles, Kings and Red racers.
Hunted lizards when we were stuck. Four are Uta?.
In the evening went out in the marsh and picked up a number of Hyla regilla. They were calling. Also went out around the lade. Heard splashes which might have been caused by the large frogs which Braumlette says are planted there but didn't see any.
The east base of the sierras is quite bare of vegetation. The mountains east of the valleys are largely volcanic - great masses of black lava.

Page Edit History:

1930 Thursday 20, Feb.

Today started with the family for Death Valley at 4 P.M. A cloudy cool day with some rain. 62 miles in the country; nothing seen arrived at Mojaive at 11:15 P.M. Very cold and windy. Went by way of Psadena, San Fernando, Mint Canyon, Lancaster.
Tried to get rooms at the latter, but had no luck. Total miles 242.
This was the first day the new running board box was used. seems to be very good.
Also today I finally succeeded in getting the gunsmith to finish the 10 inch barrel on the little Stevens .22 pistol.

Page Edit History:
  • AMS 03/14/2014 06:29 PM
  • tburress 04/11/2011 07:06 PM
  • BPOC 12/07/2010 05:26 PM

Feb Friday 21, 1930

Started from Mojave this morning at 8:40. The car had been noisy the day before account a blown exhaust gasket but the mechanic at Mojave said he had no space and that it would cause no harm.
It was clear and cool all day with little chance for specimens.
First stopped at a well in Red Rock canyon but found nothing. Stopped twice further on; once to take pictures and once to change a tire because of a roofing nail puncture. At about 11 P.M. Fowlers and Days passed. A little further on 7.7 miles south of little lake burned out a crank bearing. Waited two hours for a tow car and was then towed to little lake. Total miles 68.9.
W.W. Bramlette who runs hotel and garage advised against trying to make the repair with his mechanics so after some discussion called up San Diego and got some men started with repair parts.
Talked rattlesnakes with Bramlette who has been in this vicinity for many years and seems to know them well. He said he had caught a green velvet rattlers (undoubtedly Scututatus)
about 15 miles south of little lake. This was as far north as he had ever seen them. He also thought this was the north limit (cont. Feb 19)

Page Edit History:
  • AMS 03/14/2014 06:31 PM
  • tburress 04/11/2011 07:50 PM
  • BPOC 12/07/2010 05:26 PM

1930 Saturday 22, Feb.

Brown and a mechanic from San Diego arrived early this morning and effected repairs by noon. We left Little Lake at 2 P.M. and arrived at Riverside at 6:30. Rain much of the way; in some places quite hard. Total miles 163.
Saw some good snake country. Particularly at a point about 10 miles north of Randsbury there was a pile of rocks in the center of a valley that might be good at the opening of spring. Went via Inyokern, Randsbury and Adelanto. Road is not bad.

Page Edit History:
  • AMS 03/14/2014 06:33 PM
  • tburress 04/12/2011 12:34 PM
  • BPOC 12/07/2010 05:26 PM

Feb. Sunday 23, 1930

Returned from Riverside to San Diego today. Started at 9:30 arrived at 2 P.M. Went via Corona and took a side trip to Norconian lake country club. Saw some good snake country in Riverside Co. 2 particularly a mountain near Riverside. Too cold and wet to expect specimens although there were many dead toads in the way. Noted a dead Bufo boreas halophilus at 36.5.
County line 72.9 miles at finish 142 miles in the county 69.

Page Edit History:
  • AMS 03/14/2014 06:34 PM
  • tburress 04/11/2011 08:17 PM

1930 Monday 24, Feb.

Today Myers told me of a large red rattler killed today at Bernardo. Was found in a crack of granite. Unfortunately broke its neck tying to get it out. It measured 5' 1".
Cook told me of 3 snakes found on Saturday and Sunday. 1 Arizona 2 feet long at monument 258. It ate 2 Utas in the sack. Was found in the sand. 1 small oreganus and 1 small lateralis found in the park.
A I Benedict today brought me a large red racer taken at Banner. Was so cold when he found it he couldn't tell if it was alive or not.

Today Weinking called. He leaves tomorrow morning for lower California. Outfitted him with 2-5 gal cans, 1-1 gal can, a .22 rifle, 1500 shells, tags, cloth, directions, a shovel, 8 pts of formalin etc.

Mar. Saturday 1, 1930

Got 100 copies of the Confluentus paper. Went to Agua Caliente for lunch and did not get home until 4 P.M. 30 miles. Clear and warm. Nothing seen.
Worked on USNM specimens and finished 2. Cleaned up miscellaneous specs.

Mar. Monday 3, 1930

W.A. Rowe of San Fernando called today. Discussed the Herpetological society. He told me of a Coleonyx being found near Owens mouth, Los Angles county.
Cook found a ring neck in the park yesterday. They gave me a ring neck taken in the park for the Nat. Hist. Society.

1930 Thursday 6, Mar.

March 7th Continued
Some other lizards (probably skellies and utas) but couldn't identify the latter.

At 12:30 went with G.M. Wills to Riverside Junior College and visited with Edmund C. Jaeger until about 2 P.M. Discussed herpetology and had interesting time.

Page Edit History:
  • AMS 03/14/2014 06:42 PM
  • tburress 04/12/2011 04:24 PM
  • BPOC 12/07/2010 05:26 PM

Mar. Friday 7, 1930

Today went to Riverside and back to attend a meeting of the Interchange Committee. Started at 6:30; arrived at 9:45. Returned at 3:05 arriving at 7 P.M. Total miles 248. Miles in county during daylight hours 104. Went via new 6th st. grade and Chesterton.
In the morning on the north bound trip it was cold and very foggy in the vicinity of Temecula and Elsinore. Stopped on several occasions to turn over boards but found no salamanders. There were quite a few toads on the road but I stopped only twice to identify. Both were Bufo boreas halophilus - one 8 miles S. of Escondido the other at Red Mt.
Two D.O.R. snakes were noted - a large gopher being eaten by a buzzard at north end near Bonsall bridge and a large T. s. infernalis at Temecula (marsh on both sides.)
Coming back it was warm and pleasant. There was a large freshly killed red rattler at Perris (1 mile this side) stopped here and looked for Xantusias but found none. The rocks do not have very good flakes. Saw several nice orcuttis and [cont mar 6th]

1930 Saturday 8, Mar.

Worked on the atrox group paper all afternoon and evening and made good progress. Leda caught a ring neck near HK's.

Mar. Sunday 9, 1930

Worked on atrox paper in laboratory all day. Progress good. Rounding into shape nicely.

Cook brot in tonight for identification.

2 Rana aurora draytonii small Japatul School
2 Bufo californicus 1 large Japatul School
4 Hyla arenicolor Japatul School
1 Thamnophis ordinoides hammondi med Japatul School

Says he caught more toads and lizards; it was cold out there.

Today (Mario) saw skinks, skellies and uta stans from the same place.

Mar. Saturday 15, 1930

This morning met W.C. Hayes who is making a collecting trip into Sonora. In the afternoon and evening worked in rounding out the atrox paper. Not very good progress.

Tonight Cook, using the Max for the first time brought in a fine lot of Hyla Regilla and B.b. halophilus from Winona ave city and one Hyla from Dobe Falls.

This was the second day of a cold hard rainstorm.

1930 Sunday 16, Mar.

Went to Fowlers place near Wynola for lunch. Fowlers, Jones', Fosters and Peckham. A cold day with some rain and snow. Snow as far down as the hills west of Santa Ysabel. Start at 11:10; Returned at 6:40. 100 miles in daylight. Nothing seen except a few squashed toads.
Cook brought around tonight 4 Hyla regilla and 1 B.a. leucopus from Hodges Dam.

Mar. Sunday 23, 1930

Spent the morning working on the sketches for the atrox paper. In the afternoon went out with GG and Phil from 1:45 to 5:15. Went via Hodges Dam, San Pasqual, Ramona and home via Fletcher Hills. A fine day, very warm. 88 miles.

No live snakes were seen. A few live lizards were to be seen on rocks, none was identified. A live alligator lizard was seen crossing the road at Shady Dell.

Hunted for a few moments at one point in San Pasqual found one Hyla regilla under a cap rock much like arenicolor is usually found.
1 small gopher D.O.R. mission valley
1 garter med. D.O.R. San Pasqual
1 garter small D.O.R. Shady Dell.
Had a puncture due to a nail at Ramona. Many dead toads were seen, to dried up to identify. Cook came in tonight with a good lot of amphibians from Agua Caliente Spring, and a few lizards.

Mar. Saturday 29, 1930

This afternoon went to Fowler's place near Wynola. A warm day started at 2 P.M.; arrived at 4 P.M. 60 miles.

1 large garter D.O.R. Fletcher Hills
1 large gopher D.O.R. Lakeside

After arrival I walked around in the rocks at his place and saw a few skellies and utas. Looked under logs but found no amphibians.

Weis and Al may had a small garter for me which they had caught at the entrance to Fowler's place.

1930 Sunday 30, Mar.

This morning was cold and foggy at Wynola, not worth while hunting anything.

This morning at 9 A.M. started for Borego Valley with Raler and Hopkins. Went as far as the end of the road at Palm Canyon. It was quite cool and clear in San Felipe. In Borego Valley it was warm and comfortable but windy. Only one lizard (alive) was seen in the entire trip. No snakes. Did no hunting. Returned to Fowlers at 1 P.M. There was one C. wizliseni dead on the road near the entrance to Palm Canyon.

Came home at 4 P.M. arriving at 5:45. Cold and cloudy; nothing seen. Total miles today 146. Therefore distance from Fowler's place to end of road at Borego Palm Canyon is 43 miles.

Apr. Tuesday 8, 1930

Today at noon Gander told me of a Boyles King taken last week in the park. This can be entered. Walker found the three dead rattlers killed by the park commission in Borego Palm canyon last week. They were all reds and can be entered.

He also brought in a punctatus from Yaqui Well.
(the above should have been entered on Monday, April 7)

Today I went to El Cajon rotary at noon to make up attendance; went out via Broadway extension, returned by way of Fletcher Hills. 32 miles.
1 Large L.g. boylii D.O.R. at Chollas Hts.
1 " L. californiae " " "
(Fairmont ave.)

Tonight Cannon brought me 2 fine rattlers; also saw a red racer from Fairmont, L.A. Co.

Apr. Thursday 10, 1930

(April 11th Continued)
the road 8 miles. N.W. of Indio. Found two more D.O.R. between here and Indio, of which I saved one. Hunted along the road at 2 points but found nothing.

It was cool and windy; rather surprized that sidewinders and Arizonas should be out. On return to Indio heard some toad calling but could not find any. Found one Woodhousi dead on the road at Indio. Presume this was what I heard calling.

In a store at Palm Springs saw a large atrox skin which was said to have came from near Blythe
(6 mi. east).

1930 Sunday 13, Apr.

Started for home at 9 A.M. today. Expected to do much hunting along the road but did none at all on account of the weather. It was overcast and cool in the desert. A bad dust storm in the vicinity of Coachella. Heavy rain from Brawley to Elcanto ( where we stopped for lunch) and to Seeley. Very cold and windy in the mountains, evidently had rained the night before. It would have been useless to hunt. Reached home at 5 P.M. Total miles 214.3 Miles in county 86.1

1 Desert gopher S D.O.R. 7 miles S. of Coachella 11
1 long nose (no red) L D.O.R. Oasis 20.1
Imperial Co. line 24.0
1 Sidewinder L D.O.R. 41.5
1 Leopard Lizard L D.O.R. 43.1
1 " Lizard L D.O.R. 46.7
1 Sidewinder S D.O.R. 50.7
(= Kane Spring).
1 Sidewinder S. D.O.R. 55.1
El Centro = 91.8 (due to detours) at 12:45
1 Desert Gopher S D.O.R. Seeley 98.8 saved)
1 Thamnophis marcianus D.O.R. 2 mi W Seeley 100.8
(Continued to April 7th)

Apr. Monday 14, 1930

Milked rattlers this noon. Got a fair lot of ruber venom. Not much of anything else.

Walker brought in some fair material - not very much.

Cook phoned in this morning he was stuck with the Max at Buckman's. Sent out to get him. He brought in quite a lot of stuff. Was particularly interested in what seemed to be a large Arizona gopher, Sayi affinis from Calif.

All his stuff will be pickled and therefore properly recorded except a large cerastes from 3 mi. N. of Potholes sent to Mrs. Wiley.

Also Sceloporus magister from 3 mi. N. of Bard.

Notes:

Ben Brumfield

Could the word after "affinis from" be "Calif.", i.e. California?

psully

"sayi affinis" is a species name for the Arizona Gopher Snake

1930 Tuesday 15, Apr.

(April 19th Continued)
South of the point where the road branches to Ryan, Callys and P. platyrhinos were very common. This was on a long high mesa or alluvial fan. There were rocks alongside of the road and the lizards were seen on them. If we had had time to stop a great many might have been collected. It was this way almost all the way to the shore. Utas and whips were also seen. Never saw horned toads of any species so common. The weather was a little too warm for comfort. The horned toads were usually on the sunny side of the rocks. They seldom moved and were easily caught. Below Shoshone not so much was to be seen. Probably getting too late. Reached Baker at 6:30 and had supper. Barstow at 9 P.M.

Shoshone looked good for amphibians.

Was surprised at the lack of snakes between Baker and Barstow on the pavement. Probably one side winder was seen, but couldn't be sure as when we went back it was gone.

Not a snake seen today, alive or dead.
Miles today 208.2 (and some of them pretty tough)
Miles for the trip to date 603.1

Apr. Wednesday 16, 1930

(April 18th Continued)
After arrival at Stove Pipe Wells, I hunted with a flashlight but had no results.

The prospector told me sidewinders were the only snakes to be found in the valley.

1 Arizona Small DOR Adelanto
1 Sidewinder L DOR Kramer Hills
1 Sidewinder M DOR Kramer
1 Scutulalus L DOR Atolia
1 Longnose M DOR Rademacher
(also several tortoises along here)
1 Red Racer L DOR Little Lake
1 Sidewinder M DOR Cowan
1 Collared Lizard DOR Darwin

The most disappointing thing on todays hunt was the lack of snakes in the rocks near Rademacher. I had great hopes for these.

1930 Thursday 17, April

Recd today from Myres a small boa from Escondido.

Started on Death Valley trip at 2 P.M. this afternoon with family - a clear moderately cool day. Arrived at Victorville at 7 P.M.. It was cool and comfortable. Miles in county 68. Riverside - S.B. County line 124.4. Total miles for the day 179.7

1 Boyles King M DOR Mission Valley
1 Calif garter M DOR Temecula

Was surprised at the lack of snakes today compared with a week ago.

After unpacking at Victorville we went up the road a short distance to a marsh.

Many Hyla regilla were calling and a few were seen but none caught. Found one medium Calif. garter in the marsh; evidently they hunt at night.

Went up to the Mojave river just across the highway and hunted along the east bank. Many Hylas were calling here. Also heard the familiar Pine Vally trill ascribed to Bufo Californicus. Count not believe they were here, but sure enough we got 4, 2 young and 2 adults. One was in the water, 2 on sand and one just emerging from sand. Looked for Bufos in the park (canagicus) but found none. Returned to hotel at 9 P.M.

Page Edit History:
  • AMS 03/15/2014 01:42 AM

Apr. Friday 18, 1930

This morning we started for Death Valley, at 8 A.M. A moderately cool day. Weiss and Chuck went with us. It was cool all through Mojave Desert and Indian Wells Valley but hot on arrival at Death Valley. Lizards were quite plentiful (particularly Callys) as far as Little Lake. From there on very few were seen, probably because of it being late afternoon. There was only an occasional Uta. It was cold crossing the mountain passes but got quite hot as we descended into Death Valley. Darkness overtook us at the top of Panamint Mts.

We arrived at Bungalow City (Stovepipe Wells Hotel) at 7:20 P.M. 215.2 miles for the day. Total for the trip 394.9.

We hunted only at 2 points, first at the beginning of Kramer Hills where there is a fine outcrop of rocks. Lizards were OK but no snakes. Had brake trouble at Kandsburg which led to some delay. Second stop where we took lunch and hunted quite a while was in the fine rocky hills a short distance north of Rademacher. Always thought there should be rattlers here, but found none - and lizards were disappointing. Besides those collected (which will be found recorded in collection) I saw one magister. A few lizards were collected along the way and will be found recorded in the collection.
(Continued on April 16)

Page Edit History:
  • AMS 03/15/2014 01:56 AM

1930 Saturday 19, April

This morning was quite warm. We were ready to start at 8 AM but found that my battery had been overcharged the day before and was now shorted. It took quite a while to diagnose this case after much towing by Weiss. Finally borrowed an old battery which was just good enough to load the generator and so got the car started. From now until the end of the trip we had to keep the engine running during all stops or park on a hillside. This cramped our style considerably. Weiss had 2 punctures.

Finally got started at 11 AM. It was then quite hot. First stopped about 2 mi. South of the hotel and hunted in the sandy hummocks surmounted by greaswood and mesquite. Never saw dips so common before as here. Every bush seemed to have one or more; could have shot a 100 in a half hour. Also there were a few whiptails (see specimen list) There were utas around the hotel, and maybe callys.

Stopped at Furnace Creek Inn and had a light lunch (not in the Inn). Saw Utas here. It was then so late we had to miss seeing the lower end of the valley. We then started out by way of Ryan and Shoshone, Baker and Yermo
(Continued on April 15)

Apr. Sunday 20, 1930

Started from Barstow for home this morning at 8:45. A little too warm for comfort.

Stopped at several points along the road to hunt especially near Wild, Hillsdale, near Oro Grande and near Victorville in the rocky hill on the road to Lucerne Valley. Lizards were moderately common. The last named point was good for chucks, whips, utas and collard lizards. Also saw one magister here; the only species seen and not collected. After leaving Victorville no more collecting was done. The tree Yucca country between Victorville and Cajon Pass looks good.

1 Sidewinder DOR L Lenwood
1 Platyrhinos Caught Hodge
1 Salvadora DOR L Hodge
1 Desert Gopher DOR L Hodge
1 Sidewinder Caught M Wild
1 Scute DOR M Helendale (saved)
1 Arizona DOR M Helendale
1 Sidewinder DOR L Bryman
1 Red Racer DOR L Oro Grande
1 Salvadora DOR M Oro Grande
(Continued on April 1)

Apr. Saturday 26, 1930

This afternoon started for Yuma with the family at 2:05. A rather cool, windy day.
Did not stop on the way out except for a few moments at a reservoir near the canal where we hunted for toads but found nothing.
1 medium Patchnose DOR 29.44 Alpine (grade)
County Line 86.6
1 Trimorphodon L DOR 93.1, beyond Myers Creek Bridge. Sand on both sides of the road.
1 dip DOR 151.9
do 153.2 (Midway Wells)
1 gopher medium caught crossing the road just before 7 P.M. (quite dark) at 176.
State line at 183.5
Final miles for the night 206.8
After getting the hotel rooms we went east about 10 miles and hunted on the Yuma Mesa, but got nothing. Also looked for toads under lights and at one place down the river. All blank.
Found the town much agog account Fox Film with about 500 people engaged in filming The Oregon Trail.

1930 Sunday 27, Apr.

In the morning at about 815 we started eastward to try the Gila Mts. It was warm (not hot) and rather breezy. Went to the end of the paved road (25.6 mi.) and then turned back to Yuma. Hunted at 2 points 24 mi. E. of Yuma in the Gila Mts and 14 mi E. of Yuma on the mesa. Did not see anything except specimens as recorded (2544-60)
The dips are quite wary. Noted that they raise up rather slowly both front and rear to spy around. After a light lunch in Yuma started for home at 12.10
Yuma 51.2
Hunted in Sand Hills for Umas at 68.3 and got quite a few. They act as usual. Started from here at 140 P.M.
In the neighborhood of Brawley and El Centro I passed up a couple that probably were dead snakes.--too much hurry. Broke down about 3 mi E. of Coyote Wells and came in by stage, arriving at 830. Heard Hyla regilla at Descanso
Pickled a sidewinder tonight that contained remains of a sidewinder Uma and a caterpillar
(cont April 25/30)

Apr. Monday 28, 1930

1930 Tuesday 29, Apr.

Today at 840 we started for Ensenada--Raber, Fowler, Holloway, Weiss, Ayres, Peckham. Picked up Moreno at Tia Juana. 2 cars. It was a cold day, cloudy and with some rain and mist throughout. No day for hunting snakes.
Had lunch at the halfway house. Did not try to hunt on the way but saw a number of likely locations particularly 44 mi N. of Ensenada.
1 Large Boyles King DOR at Chula Vista
1 small gopher DOR at " "
After arrival at Ensenada we went on south to the edge of the Maneadero Valley thence back to Ensenada and up the Ensenada Arroyo for about a mile. Here we hunted in the rocks for a few moments and found 1 Coleonyx. Xantusia hunting was negative but this proves nothing as the weather was so poor.
Miles to Tia Juana 17, Total in Mexico for the day 87.8.
At Halfway House saw some rattler skins 4 reds, 1 Pacific, 1 Mitchelli all said to have been taken near here. One red had spots open on the side like Mitchellii Molossus.

May Friday 16, 1930

Pickled specimens.
Had a long nose found run over on the road at La Mesa. Couldn't save it.

Tonight I heard the call of Bufo cognatus from specimens in my basement. While there was some resemblance to Bufo californicus yet it was much less musical; more of a chatter, less of a trill. This cognatus sound is what I heard at Yuma.

May Sunday 18, 1930

Today was a clear cool day with some breeze. Everything quite wet in the back country after a rain yesterday and a week of cold weather.

Hunted for about an hour in the rocks beyond Jacumba before lunch and west of Jacumba after lunch. Got a few lizards of usual species. There were not many out. May Tuesday 20, 1930

This morning I spent about 1/2 hour looking over Weinberg's collection. He is still in Mexico but Mrs. Weinberg showed me around. They have a number of good things including a worm snake from Arizona, several Sonoras, a good series of rattlers etc. but as usual nothing definite is known concerning the localities. Saw a Sonora (from Palm Springs?) with brown bands on a white background and no red or yellow.

At noon I got several specimens from Colburn.

In the late afternoon I spent about 15 minutes at Tex Schubach. He had the usual collection of rattlers- many atrox and scutes. Also some from San Diego County. He had some nice racers particularly black and reds from Arizona and one particularly was black anteriorly (solid) and had a red posterior half. So in Arizona the two forms are not definitely separated.

Returned to S.D. at 7:40pm. Count only 30 miles in the county.

1 Boyles King L DOR Laguna Beach.
1 Red Racer L DOR Dana Point.

Notes:

Kaye London

3rd sentence- ??? of rattlers. 2nd paragraph- specimens from ???? Last paragraph- I can't read the 2 words before 30 miles in the county

May Saturday 24, 1930

Today I went out in the desert with Slevin starting from San Diego at 2pm; and arriving at Banning at 12:30am. It was cool in town and hot in the desert but we did not get to El Centro junction until about 6pm so it was reasonably cool. Had supper at Westmoreland. Route taken Broadway Extension, Spring Valley, Grossmont, highway to El Centro Junction, thence via highway to Banning. Miles in San Diego County 85.7. Total miles 258.0. Did not hunt any place. The wind was very bad at times, not bad at others. Was particularly bad up to 9pm and also in San Gorgonio pass.

Lost only one snake, an unknown north of Westmoreland.
1 Gopher M DOR Chollas Hts.

1930 Sunday 25, May

Started with Slevin from Banning at 8:30 this am. A moderately warm day in Riverside and the interior- cool at San Diego.

First hunted in some rocks near Moreno, Riv. Co. Got a Coleonyx and S. orcutii.

Went in to Riverside and then partway up Mt. Rubidoux but the rocks did not look good - hard and no flakes - so did not hunt.

Hunted a short time 2 mi. W of Perris. Got a few lizards including horned toads alive. The rocks are hard and poor.

Hunted 7 mi S.W. of Perris near Good Hope Mine. Here the rocks are better with some flakes, but no Xantusias were in evidence. Had lunch at Elsinore.

Stopped to take movies in boulders south of Lake Hodges and worked with a red rattler over an hour until something went wrong with the camera.

Reached home at 4:15. Total miles 158.7. Miles in the county 68.

For snakes checked see May 22nd.

May Friday 30, 1930

Today went to Blythe with Slevin and Philip. Started 9:15 AM. It was very cold from San Diego to the mountains. Warm but not hot at El Centro where we had lunch. We reached Blythe at 7:30 and had supper. The country from Shaver's Well east to Blythe is much like the Mojave. All the way from Westmoreland to Blythe it was cool and very windy. Somewhat less so in the river valley of the Colorado.

After supper, we drove east to the toll bridge and saw 4 large Atrox taken on the Arizona side. We then turned back westward and drove along the highway for about 30 miles. But it was so cold and windy that we got nothing although Bogert got a Sonora and Cook a Phyllorhynchus.

Made camp 10 miles west of Blythe, turning in at 10:30. Total miles for the day 346. Miles in San Diego County 86.8.

On the whole the day was quite disappointing on account of the weather.
(Continued Thursday May 29th)

June Sunday 1, 1930

Started from the California side at 9 A.M.
A good warm day with little breeze. First drove to the bridge 1.5 miles and had breakfast.

Saw whips and a skelly (probably magister)in the river bottom 5 mi. W. of the bridge, but did not collect.

Stopped at the bluff 6 mi. W. of the bridge and hunted for a short time. Collected Dips and Uta stans. Saw whips but did not collect. Callisaurus 13.3 W. of Yuma.

Next hunted until noon in the Sand hills 16.1 mi. W. of the river. Worked too hard here and tired myself out. Collected Umas, Uta graciosas and 1 dip. Noted that the Umas bob their heads. Also often run in a small circle.

1 Platyrhinos 9.8 mi. W, of River
1 Cally 11.3 mi. W. of River
1 Cally 13.3 mi. W. of River
1 Dip 22.8 mi. W. of River
1 Leopard L 25.2 mi. W. of River
1 Dip 28.5, 30, 35.5, 41.2 mi. W. of River

Dips were very plentiful for 10 miles west of Midway Well.
(Continued on May 6)

June 5, 1930

Today I went to the meeting of the Herp. Soc. of California in L.A with Philys. Staterd at 3:50 arrived at 7:50 a clear warm day-the first hot day of the season. Took up a dozen specimens of my own to show.
1 Red Racer DOR L Moreno
1 Gopher DOR L Oceanside
1 Red Racer DOR L Galivan.
Miles inside the county 61.5
A number of good specimens were on exhibit. Cannon gave me 5 rattles which will be entered through zoo list, and Bogert gave me a number of good things which will be entered through collection list.
Hayes had an exhibition of atrox and 2 (apparently) basiliscus; localities said to be the following:
atrox guaymas
atrox guaymas 2 way bet guaymas hermosillo
Baiiliscus do (no doubt molossus)
The baiiliscus look like molossus except that the forward blotches are not opened and extended laterally.

Aug. Sunday 10, 1930

Spent most of the day pickling specimens. Altogether in the past 2 days 60 rattlers have been added to the collection. I find that the new scheme of removing and expanding the pens takes considerably longer than the old scheme of merely tying off.

As of this date everything is pickled except 4 rattlers (1 tigris, 1 mitch, 1 pricei, 1 willardi) 2 gophers, 3 racers and a miscellaneous lot of lizards from Harry James.

Am beginning to feel the alcohol shortage. Only 9 gallons left.

1930 Saturday 23, Aug.

Went out to Boulder Park just beyond Jacumba today to meet Gloyd + Smith. Started at 8:30 got there about 11:30. Hunted around Boulder Park for a while (in Imperial Co as I now know) and got Xantusia henshawi; Uta stans; Uta microscute and a brood of Sceloporus magister (all in one bush). Went to Jacumba for lunch. Came on a hard rain with thunder. Then to town. Home at 5:30. Sultry.

1 Gopher small DOR Terrinitos
1 Oreganus L Live Oak Springs DOR
1 Ruber M DOR Jacumba
1 Unknown lost crossing the road at Flinn Springs. Small probably garter.
160 miles.

Sept. Tuesday 9, 1930

Went to Pasadena today starting at 9:45; arrived at 2:30. 61 miles in the county - nothing seen in the county.

1 Pacific Rattler Med DOR bet Dana Pt + Coast Royal, Orange Co.

Looked in at Schubach's place, Long Beach. Found he has gone on the road with a medicine show. His snake show has changed for the worse and is no longer worth seeing.

Late in the afternoon went into LA and saw Weinberg. Heard the story of his arrest at Nogales and the difficulty of getting data on the specimens taken on his trip.

He had a number of interesting specimens but as usual no definite locality data so made no records.

Sept. Sunday 21, 1930

Showed the collection to Bogert this AM. He gave me a large rattler from Zion and also traded for a mitchellii from Lucerne Valley.

He showed me the following preserved specimens from his recent trip.
1 Trimorphodon 1 mi. N. of Springdale, Utah
Phyllorhynchus 3 mi. E. of Barstow on road to Daggett.
Sonora occipitalis 1.2 mi. E. of Goffs.

The Trimorphodon is like a very dark lyrophanes. The spots are quite irregular. The anal is clearly divided. The ground color between spots is very dark and punctated. There were about 30 spots.

Veale came around this evening to talk over plan of monophraphing Phymosoma.

Page Edit History:
  • HerpVolunteer 05/05/2014 05:04 PM
  • AMS 03/17/2014 03:10 PM
  • BPOC 12/07/2010 05:26 PM

1930 Monday 22, Sept.

Recd today from Pappert, meter reader a small Cal. King from National City.

Talked this afternoon with J.T. Wright re collecting in Southeast Sonora. He is going down on a long collecting trip in a short while. Offered him $100 a piece for not to exceed 50 rattlers, not too many from one place. May be small. Formalin preserved or alive. Will see him again before he goes.

Crotalus ruber

Lampropeltis californiae

Arizona elegans occidentalis

Masticophis flagellum frenatus

and about a week ago Masticophis lateralis

These specimens are quite evidently this years crop and probably recently born or hatched.

293 - 1930 Monday 20, Oct.

Today recd from Henry Shelton a small rattler (oreganus) taken on north shoulder of south peak of Cuyamaca. Was found inside of a screen porch.

Also he told me of a brood found on September 20th. They first found one or two crawling loose while engaged in overturning rocks. Then under a large flat rock the found the mother and a number of little ones. There were eleven young all together including those which were crawling about. The species was oreganus. When the large rock was overturned the mother seemed to try to protect her young and did not try to escape until all were killed.

310 - Nov. Thursday 6, 1930

Chambers=206 a broad river valley with bluffs in the distance. Flat, brown, light brush. Snow again. Same small mesas in the distance. As far as the rattlers along the RR are concerned they would have a flat prairie.

Same at Cheto. A few bluffs in the vicinity. Snowing outside.

197 Junipers again. Must be going up.

194 still climbing. Rocky bluffs all about. No more prairie. Junipers and shrubs. Many rocks.

Houck. Rolling but cut up prairie again. Later palin prairie all the way into Gallup. Sage brush. 525 and almost dark at Gallup.

Page Edit History:
  • SVielma 03/15/2014 04:55 AM
  • BPOC 12/07/2010 05:26 PM

311 - 1930 Friday 7, Nov.

(continued from Nov 11)

At 258 more rough, rocky and rolling. Still red and red brown soil. Sparse vegetation. Many rocky bluffs.

At Hollbrook there are flats with rocky bluffs. (miles 253) The soil is gray brown but becomes quite red again east of Holbrook, where the red strata is exposed.

At 248 less red, more level again.

Carrizo=238 +. Red brown, rolling prairie with a river and trees on one side.

Navajo-Apache Co. line. Rolling prairie, thin grass and small bushes.

Adamana (Petrified forest 6 mi. S). Red brown rolling prairie. Very few buildings between RR stations. There are outcrops of rock bet. Adamana and Bibo.

At 223 still a rolling prairie. Bushes a little larger. Soil red brown. Rocky bluffs close by.

Navajo=213. Same rolling prairie and red brown soil. Small bushes

(continued on Nov 6)

315 - 1930 Tuesday 11, Nov.

Armistice Day

Getting ready for a trip to Chicago

Continued from Nov 12.

At 313 short grass prairie. Practically no brush. Cut by occasional canyons. Canyon Diablo at 312. Typical prairie with some rocks.

At 305 the soil had turned red and red outcrops stick up around. Grass somewhat sparse.

Very red and somewhat rolling at 300. Moqui (MP293) very red flat and rocky with a few distant buttes.

At Winslow the soil is still red. Vegetation sparse. Country flat. Hills in the distance. Some rocks.

Est of Winslow it is still quite red. Grass and some brush, rather sparse. At 280 soil not quite so red. Country a little more rolling.

At Havre. Somwhat rolling with short brush. Soil still quite red.

At 263 still red, slightly rolling, with water courses.

(continued on Nov 7)

Page Edit History:
  • HerpVolunteer 05/06/2014 04:02 PM
  • SVielma 03/15/2014 03:38 AM
  • BPOC 12/07/2010 05:26 PM

316 - Nov. Wednesday 12, 1930

Left today for Chicago

Spent the night in L.A.

Continued from Nov 13.

At MP392 some snow. Still climbing Rolling country with rocks and trees. Red brown soil. At MP391 Quite hilly. Plenty snow.

Williams at noon. Plenty snow. Have been conifers for about 10 miles. Plains to the north, mountains to the south. Snowing.

Maine Sta. a rather level country y conifers. Mts in the distance.

Flagstaff. Large conifers. Rocky hills. Much snow.

MP334. Conifers replaced by large junipers. Small level fields amid hills. Plenty snow, but less.

MP323. More barren and flatter. Junipers are smaller. Little snow. This begins to look like typical prairie country.

A few hills in the background. At 319 it is quite flat. Junipers have disappeared, snow nearly gone. Typical prairie, some yellow sandstone scattered about. Soil yellow grass short. (cont to Nov 11)

Page Edit History:
  • HerpVolunteer 05/06/2014 04:03 PM
  • SVielma 03/15/2014 03:30 AM
  • BPOC 12/07/2010 05:26 PM

317 - 1930 Thursday 13, Nov.

Interchange meeting.

Left L.A. for Chicago in the evening.

Continued from Nov. 14th

Very red in fact, the first I have seen. There are oaks here.

Another grass plain at Pica. Cold here at 10 AM.

Seligman. Another plain surrounded by rocky hills. Passed one very red outcrop. MP 429. Temp 40º F.

Crookton. Rolling country. Red brown soil. Some rocks. Frequent large junipers. Regular trees. Missed Gleed. Pineveta. rolling plain, with gray rocks. Have come down from Crookton.

Ash Fork. A rolling plain with sparse vegetation. Junipers. Plenty of snow covered mts. to the north. Then rolling hills, red brown soil. Plenty junipers and stones. Mountains to the south.

East of Ash Fork about 10 mi we climb again. Still red brown soil. Snow covered mts to the east.

Continue climbing E. of Ash Fork MP397 Many junipers, grass & stones (cont to Nov 12)

Page Edit History:
  • HerpVolunteer 05/06/2014 04:05 PM
  • SVielma 03/15/2014 03:22 AM
  • BPOC 12/07/2010 05:26 PM

318 - Nov. Friday 14, 1930

Woke up this morning 8 mi. E. of Kingman. This is a level somewhat sandy bunch-grass plain with occasional mesquite. There are plenty of mountains in the distance to the north.

Same at Antares. Somewhat undulating and cut by washes.

The mountains are now getting closer. More sagebrush. More undulating.

At Hackberry the mountains are close with brown rock. From here on we climb up and it becomes increasingly mountainous and rocky. Junipers begin to appear. Then up on the mesa at MP471 it is an undulating plain again.

Then come alternating small plains and low rocky mts.

At Peach Springs it is rocky but there are no high mts. Hilly and rocky with Junipers at Nelson. Another rolling plain at Fields. High enough for plenty of junipers. This alternates with low rocky mts.

Flat but rocky at Yampai. Going down into heaby large junipers. Some red soil.

(cont to Nov 13)

323 - 1930 Wednesday 19, Nov.

324 - Nov. Thursday 20, 1930

Enroute from Green River, Wyo. westward.

Woke up at Green River at 7 AM Train about 2 hours late. For the first ten miles west of Green River there is certainly no barrier to confluentus. The conductor says this is quite warm in summer but too high to be hot. There are rolling brush covered hills. The ground is brown from shale. The brush is sparse and low. The hills appear less than 1000 ft high. Altogether it looks like good snake country.

A few miles further (826 from Omaha) it is so level as to be almost a prairie. Sparse low brush. Must look like a desert in summer. Snow covered now. Same at 833. A broad flat valley for many miles. Same at 844.

Broad rolling plains at Granger. Still the same rolling plains at 871.

Carter. Still the same.

At 885 more hilly with a few scrubby trees. This is Bridger. Still looks like good snake country

(continued on Nov. 21)

Page Edit History:
  • HerpVolunteer 05/06/2014 04:11 PM
  • SVielma 03/15/2014 02:50 AM
  • BPOC 12/07/2010 05:26 PM

325 1930 Friday 21, Nov.

Arrived in S.F. in the morning. Business all day.

Continued from Nov 20th

At 897 quite rough, snadstone hills. Scrub junipers. But no bar to confluentus. if not to cold in summer. Hills maybe 500 ft. high. This is Spring Valley.

At Asoen tunnel still same rolling country. The tunnel goes through a hill, not a mountain.

Beyond Altamount rolling hills again with some good sized mts. Same at 913 and Evanston.

Wyuta. Rolling prairrie 943 beginning to be quite rough. Some real mts. But snakes could filter through the canyons.

950 Going down a canyon with 1000 ft sides. Plenty snow.

Echo. Canyon wider.

Henefer Valley considerably wider.

959 Canyon narrow again. Winding. Snow. Widens out again at 965. Quite wide at Morgan narrow again 8 or 9 miles from Ogden.

Northern Nevada is a detrital sage bush plain spotted with mountains.

333 - 1930 Saturday 29, Nov.

Worked on rattler sheets today while listening to the Stanford - Dartmouth game.

As of today all primary scale counts in all the rattlers in my collection (and the few in NH collection as well) have been made and entered on proper sheets. These counts include:

Scale Rows, Ventrals, Candals, Supralabials, Infralabials, Head Dimensions, Body Blotches and Rattles.

In addition complete scale counts and sheets have been made on all species which have been studied up to beginning of 1930. I will now proceed to complete the scale counts on the species I propose to investigate this winter especially Confluentus ssp. and Tigris.

339 - 1930 Friday 5, Dec.

Dictated the first very rough draft of the proposed snakes and Autos paper. The tables up to date in preliminary form were worked out on the train going east.

Today I noted carefully the method of rattling of an adanteus The motion is clearly sideways that is the short way of the rattle --O-- This could be seen clearly as this snake rattled (in tending to quiet down) by spasms dic single or double jerks or twitches.

Notes:

SVielma

347 - 1930 Saturday 13, Dec.

Did not make much progress with scale counting today. In the morning I made a careful canvas of the cerberus - confluentus contact between Gleed, Ariz and Valle, Ariz and concluded that integradation is evident. Then talked at length with Dr. Summer re predatory animal control etc.

In the afternoon went to the Annual meeting of the Fellows of the Nat. Hist. Society.

As of this date I am about half through with the confluentus caught this year. Have 49 more to do.

349 - 1930 Monday 15, Dec.

Did not have a fruitful day today. Finished the 10 Adamara specimens and 24 Platterville. The latter go more slowly a/c recording more data. Made a careful survey of a series of Colo, N.M. and Arizona confluentus spreading out 126 for this purpose. Made general notes concerning the color and form changes. This took quite a time.

Have decided it will be best if I am to proceed with the Confluentus - Tigris - Enyo paper that it will be in order to proceed with the map work first. This will involve considerable correspondence and to get replys in time should be under way.

Started Cook measuring rattles on the Platterville series.

GG sprained her ankle

made good headway tonight on mapping confluentus.

Lampropeltis californiae

Pages:

Lampropeltis getula

California King snake

L.g. boylii refers to the subspecies of king snake which has a ringed pattern.

L.g. californiae refers to the subspecies of king snake which has a striped pattern.
